<h2 id="cause-effect">Cause and Effect</h2><p><strong>因为…所以… (yīnwèi…suǒyǐ…)</strong> Because…therefore… Example: 因为下雨，所以我不去 (Because it's raining, I'm not going). Note: in Chinese, you can use both halves of the pair or just one.</p>
    <h2 id="contrast">Contrast</h2><p><strong>虽然…但是… (suīrán…dànshì…)</strong> Although…but… Example: 虽然很累，但是很开心 (Although tired, I'm happy). Unlike English, Chinese uses both "although" AND "but" in the same sentence.</p>
    <h2 id="condition">Condition</h2><p><strong>如果…就… (rúguǒ…jiù…)</strong> If…then… Example: 如果明天不下雨，我就去 (If it doesn't rain tomorrow, I'll go). <strong>只要…就… (zhǐyào…jiù…)</strong> As long as…then… These connector pairs are key to expressing complex ideas in Chinese.</p>
